Believers in free trade
From Cambridge — — Recently, I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues of mine. "I must warn you."
One of them warned me beforehand, saying, "These students are strong advocates of globalization."
He asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, with over 90 percent favoring the former.
And even before the magic effects of comparative advantage were introduced.
We know that using the same questions to survey a representative sample — rather than Harvard students — in real surveys would yield a completely different result.
The ratio of opponents of trade restrictions to supporters in the United States is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students would not come as a surprise.
Because those with higher technical skills and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students had already anticipated their future (prospects) and made decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they simply do not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different form, emphasizing the distributional effects that trade might bring about.
The consensus in favor of fair trade has vanished even more quickly than I anticipated.
At the beginning, I asked everyone if they agreed that I would conduct a particularly magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, then told them that I had a way to make the $200 disappear from Nicholas's account—poof!—while adding $300 to John's. The grand feat of social engineering could add an extra $100 in value to the class as a whole.
Would they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small fraction strongly agreed, while many were uncertain, and even more opposed implementing this change.
But the responses from Harvard students would not come as a surprise.
Clearly, the students could not tolerate such a significant form of income redistribution, even when the size of the economic pie is increased.
I then asked why, despite this, the majority of them seemed almost instinctively to support free trade, which in fact also leads to a similar—indeed, even more significant—redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students seemed stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John both have competing small companies.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced a better product, so he not only ended up with an additional $300 compared to Nicholas but also drove his competitor out of the market and caused him to lose $200.
How many students then supported this change?
Most voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another assumption directly related to international trade.
If John was able to drive Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully protected?
Or employing child labor in Indonesia?
The level of agreement with the change decreased accordingly with the above options.
Moreover, technological innovation, like trade, can put certain individuals at a disadvantage. What is your stance on this?
Few students were willing to curb the development of technology.
For almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs to preserve the candle-makers' jobs is a silly idea.
Therefore, what students oppose may not be redistribution itself, but certain specific forms of it.
Like most of us, they are concerned about the fairness of the program.
If we are to judge the outcomes of income redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that produce such outcomes.
We do not resent Bill Gates or Warren Buffett for their enormous wealth, even though some of their competitors have struggled for a long time, perhaps because they and their competitors operate according to the same basic rules and face similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become rich through fraud, violating labor laws, destroying the environment, or benefiting from subsidies provided by foreign governments, our views would be quite different.
If we cannot tolerate income redistribution achieved through violations of widely accepted moral standards at home, how can we justify it when it involves international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect the redistribution effects to achieve equality in the long term, with everyone ultimately benefiting, we will likely not mind the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative consequences to certain individuals, we are still willing to promote its development.
While on the other hand, when trade continually impacts the same group — low-skilled blue-collar workers — we become concerned about globalization.
But many economists ignore these clear differences.
They tend to attribute their concerns about globalization to stupid and selfish protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most crucial issue is actually moral.
Because these economists fail to recognize that international trade, while not always, sometimes leads to distributional consequences that we would find unacceptable domestically, they are unable to appropriately engage in public discourse.
And since their arguments on moral grounds don't hold water, how can they defend trade vigorously?
When globalization occasionally triggers a tricky issue related to the legalization of redistribution effects, we should not respond impulsively by imposing trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons to weigh, including the fact that globalization may deprive others of their wealth to an even greater extent than it does victims in the United States.
But democratic nations should have a more appropriate discussion on this and make conscious and more considered decisions.
And the盲目迷恋全球化仅仅因为它做大了蛋糕，而不假思索地接受其带来的再分配效应，则必将长期侵蚀全球化的合法性。
